450. Fiet Aristarchum] Aristarchus, whose name was proverbial among the an- cients as a critic, was born in Samothracia about ac. 730. He passed the greater part of his life at Alexandria under the patronage of Ptolemaeus Philopator, Epi- phanes, and Philometor, the second of whom he educated.

Celsus says it is so called because the remedies resorted to were chiefly amuse- ments and indulgences to keep up the spirits, such as none but the ric-h could afford. (See Pliny xxii. 24, ξ 53.)
